[2] VEE - Belize: news report
Date: Wed 2 Sep 2009
Source: Love News FM [edited]
<http://www.lovefm.com/ndisplay.php?nid=10707>


Horse infections detected in Belize
-----------------------------------
The Belize Agricultural Health Authority, BAHA, has confirmed that
equine encephalomyelitis viruses are circulating in Belize. These
viral diseases are transmitted by mosquitoes and alternate infection
of birds or rodents. Outbreaks have been detected in the Belize,
Stann Creek, and Cayo Districts. Love News spoke to Doctor Miguel
Depaz, who is a veterinary officer for BAHA at central Farm.

Doctor Miguel Depaz: veterinary officer, BAHA
"Normally we have a few cases of equine encephalomyelitis every year;
sporadic cases. The reason why we are making this report is because
we are having an increase in the number of cases but more so in Cayo.
We are having cases in horses; the name of the disease is Venezuelan
equine encephalomyelitis and it is transmittable to humans because
the vector is mosquitoes. We say it is a zoonotic disease because it
can be transmitted to humans. It affects the nervous system so you
have incoordination, the horses don't seem to know where they are; we
refer to that as stupor. They also have tremors but basically it is
the nervous system that is affected. It would be transmitted by
mosquitoes to humans, you would get flu like symptoms."

Doctor Depaz says that the risk of infection can be reduced if horse
owners vaccinate their horses, a move that BAHA is strongly
recommending. He also gave some advice to other Belizeans.

Doctor Miguel Depaz: veterinary officer, BAHA
"Because it is transmitted by mosquitoes you want to keep water
ponds, containers, and tires far away. So if you can do some spraying
to get rid of the mosquitoes we know that at this time of the year
there is an increase of mosquitoes and because mosquitoes are the
vectors you want to get rid of the mosquitoes."

Additional information can be obtained from BAHA at telephone number 824-4899.

--
